Sure! I can help you create a database for your blog in MySQL with two tables: "post" and "category". Here's an example of how you can create those tables:

```sql
CREATE DATABASE blog;

USE blog;

CREATE TABLE category (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE post (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    content TEXT NOT NULL,
    category_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (category_id) REFERENCES category(id)
);
```

In this example, the "category" table has an ID column (to uniquely identify each category) and a name column to store the category name. The "post" table has an ID column (to uniquely identify each post), a title column to store the post title, a content column to store the post content, and a category_id column to associate each post with a category (this creates a simple relationship between the post and category tables).

Please note that relationships are essential in databases to establish connections between tables, enable data consistency, and improve data integrity. However, if you specifically do not want any relationship rules in your database, you can use the provided example.
